Background

On applying the cellcycleR method on Yoav data across all genes, the cellcycleR seemed to be picking up the ribosomal proteins. Also when these ribosomal proteins were removed, it was picking up heat shock and other genes that are related to cell cycle. In this script, we only focus on genes that are associated with CDC, cyclin and other cell cycle specific activities. This is just to see if CDC and cyclin related genes which should be informative about cell phases are so or not.

Removing the ribosomal genes

setwd('/Users/kushal/Documents/singleCell-method/project/analysis')
colnames <- colnames(read.table("../data/batch_removed_counts_all_genes.txt"));
molecules_single <- data.frame(fread("../data/batch_removed_counts_all_genes.txt"), row.names = 1);
colnames(molecules_single) <- colnames
cycle_counts_data <- molecules_single;
dim(cycle_counts_data)
## [1]   578 17084
cycle_voom_data <- voom(cycle_counts_data)$E;
cycle_data_norm <- apply(cycle_voom_data,2,function(x)  return (x-mean(x))/sd(x))
celltime_levels <- 100;
cycle_data_norm <- cycle_data_norm[, which(colSums(cycle_data_norm)!=0)]

dim(cycle_data_norm)
## [1]   578 16860

Next we use the mygene package to annotate all the genes and save the output as a rda file.

out <- queryMany(colnames(cycle_data_norm),  scopes="ensembl.gene", fields=c("name","summary"), species="human");

query_names <- out$query;
unique_query_names <- unique(query_names);

annotate_genes <- out[match(unique_query_names, query_names),];
save(annotate_genes, file="../rdas/annotate_all_genes.rda")

Filtering the CDC and cyclin related genes.

Filtering out the ribosomal genes

annotate_genes <- get(load("../rdas/annotate_all_genes.rda"));
filter1 <- grep("CDC", annotate_genes$name)
filter2 <- grep("cyclin", annotate_genes$name)
filter3 <- grep("cell cycle", annotate_genes$name)
filter <- unique(c(filter1,filter2, filter3))

annotate_genes_filtered <- annotate_genes[filter,];
gene_names_filtered <- annotate_genes_filtered$query;

labeling_indices <- match(gene_names_filtered, colnames(cycle_data_norm))
cycle_data_norm <- cycle_data_norm[,labeling_indices];

The cell phases as assigned using Macosko method

cell_phases <- as.vector(as.matrix(read.table("../data/cell_phase_vector_yoav.txt")));

apply cellcyleR on the cyclin, CDC and cell cycle regulator genes

out <- cell_ordering_class(cycle_data_norm, celltime_levels = 100, num_iter=100, save_path="../rdas/cell_order_ipsc_cdc_cyclin.rda")

We ran the method above once already (took around 30 minutes) and now we just load the output.

out <- get(load(file="../rdas/cell_order_ipsc_cdc_cyclin.rda"));
cell_order_full <- cell_ordering_full(out$signal_intensity, dim(cycle_data_norm)[2])

We look at the plots of the amplitudes, phases and the non signal variation of the genes.

amp_genes <- out$amp;
sd_genes <- out$sigma;
phi_genes <- out$phi;

plot(density(phi_genes), col="red", main="Density plot of the phases")

plot(density(amp_genes[-which.max(amp_genes)]), col="red", main="Density plot of the amplitudes")

plot(density(sd_genes[-which.max(sd_genes)]), col="red", main="Density plot of the non-signal sd")

vioplot(cell_order_full[which(cell_phases=="G1.S")],
        cell_order_full[which(cell_phases=="S")],
        cell_order_full[which(cell_phases=="G2.M")],
        cell_order_full[which(cell_phases=="M")],
        cell_order_full[which(cell_phases=="M.G1")],
        names=c("G1","S","G2M","M","M.G1"),
        col="red")

We extract the genes with high SNR - these are more likely to be sinusoidal.

ESS <- amp_genes^2; RSS <- sd_genes^2

SNR <- ESS/RSS;

plot(SNR, col="red", pch=20, lwd=1)

top_genes <- which(SNR > 1);

Next we plot the qtlcharts for these top sinusoidal genes and see if their patterns are indeed sinusoidal or not.

iplotCurves(t(cycle_data_norm[order(cell_order_full),top_genes]))
## Set screen size to height=700 x width=1000

Gene Annotations

We perform gene annotations on the highly sinusoidal genes obtained from among the non ribosomal genes and see if they have cell phase related functionalities or not.

sinusoidal_gene_names <- colnames(cycle_data_norm);
imp_genes <- sinusoidal_gene_names[order(SNR, decreasing=TRUE)]
top_genes_100 <- imp_genes[1:100];

We annotate these genes using the mygene package and report them in a tabular format.

out <- queryMany(top_genes_100,  scopes="ensembl.gene", fields=c("name","summary"), species="human");

The protein encoded by this gene is a member of the INK4 family of cyclin-dependent kinase inhibitors. The abundance of the transcript of this gene was found to oscillate in a cell-cycle dependent manner with the lowest expression at mid G1 and a maximal expression during S phase. In all eukaryotes, the cell cycle is governed by cyclin-dependent protein kinases (CDKs), whose activities are regulated by cyclins and CDK inhibitors in a diverse array of mechanisms that involve the control of phosphorylation and dephosphorylation of Ser, Thr or Tyr residues. Cyclins are molecules that possess a consensus domain called the cyclin box. In mammalian cells, 9 cyclin species have been identified, and they are referred to as cyclins A through I. Cyclin G is a direct transcriptional target of the p53 tumor suppressor gene product and thus functions downstream of p53. GAK is an association partner of cyclin G and CDK5. Two transcript variants encoding different isoforms have been found for this gene. 2580 cyclin G associated kinase ENSG00000178950
The protein encoded by this gene (p35) is a neuron-specific activator of cyclin-dependent kinase 5 (CDK5); the activation of CDK5 is required for proper development of the central nervous system. The p35 form of this protein is proteolytically cleaved by calpain, generating a p25 form. The cleavage of p35 into p25 results in relocalization of the protein from the cell periphery to nuclear and perinuclear regions. P25 deregulates CDK5 activity by prolonging its activation and changing its cellular location. The p25 form accumulates in the brain neurons of patients with Alzheimers disease. This accumulation correlates with an increase in CDK5 kinase activity, and may lead to aberrantly phosphorylated forms of the microtubule-associated protein tau, which contributes to Alzheimers disease. 8851 cyclin-dependent kinase 5, regulatory subunit 1 (p35) ENSG00000176749

The protein encoded by this gene belongs to the highly conserved cyclin family, whose members are characterized by a dramatic periodicity in protein abundance through the cell cycle. Cyclins function as regulators of CDK kinases. Different cyclins exhibit distinct expression and degradation patterns which contribute to the temporal coordination of each mitotic event. The cyclin encoded by this gene was shown to be expressed in testis and brain, as well as in several leukemic cell lines, and is thought to primarily function in the control of the germline meiotic cell cycle. This cyclin binds both CDK2 and CDC2 kinases, which give two distinct kinase activities, one appearing in S phase, the other in G2, and thus regulate separate functions in cell cycle. This cyclin was found to bind to important cell cycle regulators, such as Rb family proteins, transcription factor E2F-1, and the p21 family proteins. This gene encodes a potent cyclin-dependent kinase inhibitor. The encoded protein binds to and inhibits the activity of cyclin-cyclin-dependent kinase2 or -cyclin-dependent kinase4 complexes, and thus functions as a regulator of cell cycle progression at G1. The expression of this gene is tightly controlled by the tumor suppressor protein p53, through which this protein mediates the p53-dependent cell cycle G1 phase arrest in response to a variety of stress stimuli. This protein can interact with proliferating cell nuclear antigen, a DNA polymerase accessory factor, and plays a regulatory role in S phase DNA replication and DNA damage repair. This protein was reported to be specifically cleaved by CASP3-like caspases, which thus leads to a dramatic activation of cyclin-dependent kinase2, and may be instrumental in the execution of apoptosis following caspase activation. Mice that lack this gene have the ability to regenerate damaged or missing tissue.
